In our dataset there isn’t an “initial” interest receivable balance (the beginning “Initial…” rows do not include any interest receivable entry) so we take the beginning balance as 0.00. Then we add every interest receivable transaction’s “amount” (which are for transactions whose type is “Interest Receivables”) to get the ending balance.

When we add these 35 amounts (all being recorded as “Unpaid” so they accumulate in the “receivable” balance), the sum works out approximately as follows:

 • Sum groups (rough step‐calculation):
  – Group1 (1 transaction): 374.69 
  – Group2 (2 transactions): 2×328.36728 ≈ 656.73 
  – Group3 (2 transactions): 2×314.61678 ≈ 629.23 
  – Group4 (2 transactions): 2×304.2109 ≈ 608.42

  – Group6 (4 transactions): 4×243.35332122 ≈ 973.41 
  – Group7: one transaction of 203.44 
  – Group8 (9 transactions): 9×183.67882122 ≈ 1653.11 
  – Group9 (8 transactions): 8×183.67882122 ≈ 1469.43 
  – Group10 (2 transactions): 2×183.67882122 ≈ 367.36 
  – Group11 (2 transactions): 2×176.45202122 ≈ 352.90 
Adding all these gives an ending balance of roughly 7775.44.

Thus, with an initial value of 0.00 and by summing all the “Interest Receivables” amounts, we arrive at a final interest receivable of about 7775.44.
